<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRADBURY, CAREY, REYES SELECTED IN DRAFT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE McKIBBEN and JIM LINDGREN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
San Diego area players Miah Bradbury, Frank Carey and Glen Reyes were selected 
Monday on the first day of baseball's amateur draft. 
</P>
<P>
Reyes, a track and football standout at Orange Glen High School, had not played 
baseball since his freshman year but was picked by the Houston Astros in the 
early rounds. Reyes, drafted as an infielder, is a three-time section sprint 
champion, winning the 100-meter dash two consecutive years and the 200-meter 
dash this year. In football, he caught 24 passes, averaging 18.2 yards. 
</P>
<P>
Carey, a second baseman who will graduate from Stanford this month, was 
selected by the San Francisco Giants. Carey was a four-year starter helping the 
Cardinal win College World Series championships in 1987 and 1988. At Granite 
Hills High, he set the section career stolen base mark with 95. 
</P>
<P>
Bradbury, a catcher from Mt. Carmel High who played at Loyola Marymount the 
past three years, was picked in the sixth round by the Philadelphia Phillies, 
the same team which selected him out of high school. Bradbury, a junior, hit 
.400 with six homers and 45 RBIs for the Lions this season. DAVE McKIBBEN and 
JIM LINDGREN 
</P>
</TEXT>
