<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE DRUG CLINIC: ALCOHOLISM AND 'WILLFUL MISCONDUCT' CONTROVERSY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOSEPH A. PURSCH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: Has anything been done about the recent Supreme Court decision that 
said that the disabling effects of chronic alcoholism are considered to be the 
result of willful misconduct? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: The Supreme Court decision that you are referring to was made in April, 
1988, in the case of Traynor and McKelvey vs. the Veterans Administration. It 
said, in effect, that these two veterans, who are recovering alcoholics, were 
ineligible to get an extension to utilize GI educational benefits. The decision 
sparked a lot of indignation -- both pro and con. It also marshaled an 
organized effort by the National Council on Alcoholism Inc. to change the 
Supreme Court decision. 
</P>
<P>
Congress enacted legislation on Oct. 20, 1988, that said, "The disabling 
effects of chronic alcoholism shall not be considered to be the result of 
willful misconduct." The President signed this legislation Nov. 18, 1988. Since 
then the Veterans Administration has instructed all of its affiliates that the 
new legislation is in effect. Anyone who may have regained eligibility for 
educational benefits through the change should contact his or her local VA 
office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
