<TEXT>
<P>
Share prices on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange rebounded slightly today in 
continued nervous trading over China's bloody crackdown on pro-democracy 
demonstrators. 
</P>
<P>
Trading was heavy, but brokers said they expected the market to fluctuate until 
the crisis in China stabilizes. 
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index of blue-chip stocks closed at 2,149.71, up 56.1 points from 
Monday, when it registered its worst loss since the worldwide market collapse 
in 1987. The index fell 581.77 points on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
Volume totaled $256.6 million, compared with $288 million Monday. 
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corp., the largest bank in the territory, 
again helped support share prices, officials said. The bank also intervened on 
Monday. 
